{"msg_id":"f92f747b-daf8-4d33-81b9-9bd2e8908a75","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682477365075895,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"Parent item for 7 ergonomic fixes identified from demo review. v0.8.1 is tagged, all 10 demos pass, three hosted bugs fixed. This plan implements P1-P7 fixes then rebuilds all demos with the new sugar. Design source: conversation context from comprehensive demo review.","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p0","title":"Ready CLI ergonomic improvements: reduce ceremony across all workflows","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"611e49fa-8ebb-4d3c-a7ce-5b4a6688c388","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682494668286675,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"## Outcome\nAfter rd join succeeds, rd list shows all existing items without the user running rd sync pull manually.\n\n## Design reference\nP2 from conversation context. Every demo that joins follows with rd sync pull — this is never optional.\n\n## Implementation\nFile: cmd/rd/join.go, function bootstrapJoinedProject()\nAfter creating .ready/mutations.jsonl (line ~550), add sync pull:\n1. Call requireClient() to get a protocol.Client\n2. Create a clientLister{client: client} (type already defined in cmd/rd/sync.go)\n3. Call rdSync.Pull(lister, campfireID, mutationsPath, projectDir, 0)\n4. If pull fails, fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, warning) — do NOT fail the join\n5. If pull succeeds and pulled \u003e 0, print 'synced N item(s)' to stderr\n\nThe clientLister type in sync.go wraps protocol.Client.Read() and implements rdSync.MessageLister. It was added in the ready-c6e fix.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do NOT make sync pull blocking — join must succeed even if pull fails (network flap, empty campfire, etc.)\n- Do NOT import rdSync in join.go if it creates a circular dep — if so, extract the pull logic to a shared helper in pkg/sync/\n- Do NOT change the Pull() function signature\n\n## Test\ntest-depth: feature\nWrite a test in cmd/rd/join_test.go or test/e2e/:\n1. Create hosted campfire with owner identity, create 2 items\n2. Admit member, member runs rd join\n3. Assert: rd list --all --json from member shows both items WITHOUT rd sync pull\n4. The test must use real campfire transport (hosted or filesystem), not mocks\n\n## Agent type\nagent-type: implementer\nartifact-type: code\nmodel: sonnet","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-5cd","parent_id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p1","title":"Auto-sync on join: rd join pulls history automatically","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"2e9ef1d0-3706-4bf5-9d79-efba506037a7","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682509551287386,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"## Outcome\nrd join and subsequent rd commands from a non-owner identity produce NO 'could not start in-process convention server: inbox campfire ... not in client membership list' warning.\n\n## Design reference\nP5 from conversation context. Warning appears in demos 02, 04, 05, 06, 07, 08, 09.\n\n## Implementation\nFile: cmd/rd/root.go, function requireConventionServer() (line ~91)\n\nThe warning comes from conventionserver.Server.Start() at line 119 when it tries to validate inbox campfire membership. The inbox watcher is only useful for the project owner (who created the inbox campfire and is admitted to it).\n\nFix: Before passing WithInboxCampfireID to conventionserver.New(), check if the current identity is a member of the inbox campfire. If not, skip the inbox option silently.\n\nCode change in requireConventionServer():\n```go\nif syncCfg.InboxCampfireID != \"\" {\n    // Only enable inbox watcher if we're a member of the inbox campfire.\n    // Non-owners (joiners) are not admitted to the inbox — skip silently.\n    if m, err := client.GetMembership(syncCfg.InboxCampfireID); err == nil \u0026\u0026 m != nil {\n        opts = append(opts, conventionserver.WithInboxCampfireID(syncCfg.InboxCampfireID))\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis replaces the unconditional append at line 101. client.GetMembership() is already available — client is passed as a parameter.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do NOT change conventionserver.Server.Start() itself — the fix is in the caller\n- Do NOT suppress ALL warnings from the convention server — only the inbox membership check\n- Keep the summary campfire option unconditional (summary campfire has different admission semantics)\n\n## Test\ntest-depth: bugfix\nWrite a regression test: create project with owner, admit member, member runs any rd command (e.g. rd ready). Assert stderr does NOT contain 'could not start in-process convention server'.\n\n## Agent type\nagent-type: implementer\nartifact-type: code\nmodel: sonnet","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-3ce","parent_id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p1","title":"Suppress convention server warning for non-owner joiners","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"62b62c10-ef40-49a6-931f-8eab8d6e6e16","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682545975530413,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"## Outcome\nrd init on a local filesystem campfire succeeds without --confirm and without printing durability warnings. rd init on a hosted campfire (--remote) without durability tags still warns and prompts.\n\n## Design reference\nP3 from conversation context. All 10 demos pass --confirm. Local campfires can't lose messages.\n\n## Implementation\nFile: cmd/rd/init.go, function evaluateCampfireDurability() (line ~334)\n\nThe function reads RD_CAMPFIRE_TAGS and RD_PROVENANCE env vars, evaluates trust, and warns if below minimum. For local filesystem transport, the campfire IS the filesystem — messages are files, they don't expire.\n\nFix: Add transport detection before the durability check. If the transport is filesystem (not remote), skip the durability evaluation entirely and return a SyncConfig with MeetsMinimum=true.\n\nTransport detection: check if CF_HOME has a remote config. The campfire library stores transport config in CF_HOME. Check for a remote.json or similar marker. Alternatively, simpler: check if the campfire base dir (localCampfireBaseDir()) is on the local filesystem — if it starts with a local path (not https://), it's filesystem transport.\n\nSimplest approach: in cmd/rd/init.go, check whether the client was initialized with remote transport. The protocol.Client may expose this. If not, check for the presence of a remote URL in CF_HOME config files:\n```go\nfunc isRemoteTransport() bool {\n    // Check if CF_HOME has remote config (indicates hosted campfire)\n    remotePath := filepath.Join(CFHome(), \"remote.json\")\n    _, err := os.Stat(remotePath)\n    return err == nil\n}\n```\n\nIf not remote, skip evaluateCampfireDurability entirely:\n```go\nif !isRemoteTransport() {\n    syncCfg = \u0026rdconfig.SyncConfig{CampfireID: campfireID, Durability: \u0026rdconfig.DurabilityAssessment{MeetsMinimum: true}}\n} else {\n    syncCfg, durabilityWarnings, err = evaluateCampfireDurability(campfireID, confirm)\n}\n```\n\nVerify the actual remote config file name by checking what cf init --remote writes to CF_HOME. May be config.json with a transport.url field, or a separate file.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do NOT remove durability warnings for hosted campfires — those are real\n- Do NOT change evaluateCampfireDurability() itself — change the caller in initCmd.RunE\n- Do NOT remove the --confirm flag — keep it for hosted campfires\n\n## Test\ntest-depth: feature\n1. Test: rd init with local filesystem CF_HOME, no --confirm, no env vars. Assert: exit 0, no durability warning in stderr.\n2. Test: rd init with remote CF_HOME (mock or real hosted), no --confirm, no env vars. Assert: prompts or errors (existing behavior preserved).\n\n## Agent type\nagent-type: implementer\nartifact-type: code\nmodel: sonnet","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-b56","parent_id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p1","title":"Quiet durability warnings for local filesystem campfires","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"7f82606e-4836-41bf-a724-954f6d17debb","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682561453957544,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"## Outcome\n`ITEM=$(rd create 'Ship login' --priority p1 --type task)` sets ITEM to just the item ID (e.g. 'myproject-c45') with no other text. When stdout IS a TTY, the current human-friendly message is preserved.\n\n## Design reference\nP4 from conversation context. Every demo that creates items requires python3 JSON parsing to extract the ID.\n\n## Implementation\nFile: cmd/rd/create.go, line ~240\n\nCurrent non-JSON output:\n```go\nfmt.Printf(\"created %s (msg: %s)\\n\", id, msg.ID)\n```\n\nChange to:\n```go\nif isatty.IsTerminal(os.Stdout.Fd()) {\n    fmt.Printf(\"created %s (msg: %s)\\n\", id, msg.ID)\n} else {\n    fmt.Println(id)\n}\n```\n\nThe go-isatty package is already imported in cmd/rd/root.go (github.com/mattn/go-isatty, line 15). Import it in create.go or use a shared helper.\n\nAlso apply the same pattern to:\n- cmd/rd/create.go — print ID only\n- cmd/rd/claim.go (if exists) or the claim path in update.go — print ID only  \n- cmd/rd/done.go or close path — print ID only\n\nThe key insight: when piped, print the minimum useful output (the ID). When interactive, keep the prose.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do NOT change --json output — that's already machine-parseable\n- Do NOT change stderr output (warnings go to stderr, not affected)\n- Only change stdout non-JSON output for piped mode\n- os.Stdout.Fd() is the correct check (not os.Stdin — we care about whether output is piped, not input)\n\n## Test\ntest-depth: feature\n1. Test: run rd create with stdout redirected to a file. Read file. Assert: contains only the item ID, no 'created' prefix, no msg ID.\n2. Test: run rd create with stdout as terminal (or mock). Assert: output matches 'created \u003cid\u003e (msg: ...)' pattern.\n\n## Agent type\nagent-type: implementer\nartifact-type: code\nmodel: sonnet","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-e09","parent_id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p1","title":"Pipe-friendly output: rd create prints bare ID when stdout is not a TTY","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"130edf5e-27b7-4907-8c6d-7603e03a40b5","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682596617699408,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"## Outcome\nOrchestrator runs `rd invite` → gets a token string. Worker runs `rd join \u003ctoken\u003e` → is immediately a member, synced, ready to work. No pubkey exchange.\n\n## Design reference\nP1 from conversation context. This is the highest-impact fix — eliminates the dominant ceremony across 7/10 demos. pkg/captoken/ has full Ed25519 signing, TTL tiers, offline verification — all implemented and tested, zero CLI integration.\n\n## Architecture: Pre-provisioned identity\nThe campfire protocol requires the joiner's pubkey to be admitted BEFORE they join. We can't know the pubkey until the joiner exists. Solution: rd invite pre-generates an ed25519 keypair, admits the public key, and embeds the private key in the token.\n\n### rd invite (new command)\nFile: cmd/rd/invite.go (new file)\n\nFlow:\n1. Load project campfire ID from projectRoot()\n2. Generate a fresh ed25519 keypair: pub, priv = ed25519.GenerateKey(rand.Reader)\n3. Admit the generated pubkey: call admitMember(client, campfireID, hex.EncodeToString(pub), label)\n4. Build an invite payload: {campfire_id, private_key_hex, role, ttl, issued_at}\n5. Sign with the issuer's identity key (for tamper detection)\n6. Encode: base64url(json(payload) + signature), prefix with 'rdx1_'\n7. Print to stdout\n\nFlags: --ttl (default 2h), --role (default member)\n\n### rd join \u003ctoken\u003e (extend existing)\nFile: cmd/rd/join.go\n\nIn joinCmd.RunE, detect 'rdx1_' prefix on the argument:\n1. Decode token: strip prefix, base64url decode, split payload+signature\n2. Verify signature against the issuer's pubkey embedded in the token (or skip — the admit itself is the authorization)\n3. Extract campfire_id and private_key_hex\n4. Write the pre-provisioned private key as the identity for this campfire. Options:\n   a. Write to CF_HOME/identity.json (replacing the default identity) — simple but destructive\n   b. Write to a campfire-scoped identity file and configure the client to use it — cleaner but requires campfire library support\n   c. Create a fresh CF_HOME with the pre-provisioned key, set CF_HOME for this process — cleanest for ephemeral workers\n   \n   Go with (a) for workers that have a fresh CF_HOME (the common case — demo 09 pattern). If CF_HOME already has an identity, warn and require --force. For the worker/agent use case, CF_HOME is always fresh.\n   \n   Implementation: write identity.json with the pre-provisioned key, then proceed with normal join flow (client.Join, bootstrapJoinedProject, auto-sync from P2).\n5. Print: 'joined \u003ccampfire\u003e via invite token (expires in Xh)'\n\n### Token format\n```json\n{\n  \"v\": 1,\n  \"campfire_id\": \"\u003c64-char hex\u003e\",\n  \"private_key\": \"\u003c64-char hex ed25519 seed\u003e\",  \n  \"role\": \"member\",\n  \"issued_at\": 1712600000,\n  \"expires_at\": 1712607200,\n  \"issuer\": \"\u003c64-char hex pubkey of inviter\u003e\"\n}\n```\nThe token is base64url-encoded JSON prefixed with 'rdx1_'. No separate signature needed — the admit record IS the authorization. The issuer field is informational (audit trail).\n\n### Security considerations\n- Token contains a private key — treat as secret (like an API key or SSH key)\n- TTL limits exposure window (default 2h)\n- The admitted identity is scoped to one campfire (other campfires still reject it)\n- If token leaks, the identity can be revoked via rd revoke\n- For production: consider encrypting the token payload with a passphrase\n\n## Dependencies\n- Depends on P2 (auto-sync on join) — join must auto-sync so the one-command flow works\n\n## Constraints\n- Do NOT modify pkg/captoken/ — use it as-is or build the invite token format separately (captoken is for operation-scoped tokens, invite tokens are identity-scoped)\n- Do NOT change the campfire protocol — work within the existing admit+join flow\n- Do NOT require the joiner to have an existing identity — the token provides one\n- The token MUST work with both filesystem and hosted campfires\n\n## Test\ntest-depth: feature\n1. Owner creates hosted project, runs rd invite --ttl 1h\n2. Assert: token starts with 'rdx1_', decodes to valid JSON with expected fields\n3. Worker with fresh CF_HOME runs rd join \u003ctoken\u003e\n4. Assert: worker's rd list shows owner's items (auto-synced)\n5. Worker creates an item, owner syncs and sees it\n6. Security test: expired token (set issued_at in the past) → rd join rejects it\n7. Security test: token for wrong campfire → join fails\n\n## Agent type\nagent-type: implementer\nartifact-type: code\nmodel: opus","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-c31","parent_id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p0","title":"rd invite: one-command admit via pre-provisioned identity token","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"23d00c91-c096-47fb-bde9-17a8b0cc1633","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682628291606904,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"## Outcome\n`rd dep add frontend-abc backend-xyz` succeeds when the user is a member of both campfires. The blocked item (frontend-abc) does NOT appear in rd ready until the blocker (backend-xyz) is closed.\n\n## Design reference\nP7 from conversation context. Demo 03 tries cross-project deps and gets rejected. The 'two projects, one owner' pattern is the most common multi-project use case.\n\n## Implementation\n\n### Part A: Allow cross-campfire dep add when member of both\nFile: cmd/rd/dep.go, depAddCmd.RunE (line ~36)\n\nCurrent code (lines 48-53) rejects any IsCrossCampfireRef() with an error. Change this:\n1. When a cross-campfire ref is detected, resolve it to a campfire ID\n2. Check if the current identity is a member of that campfire (client.GetMembership)\n3. If member of both: proceed with the dep add (post work:block with cross-campfire ref)\n4. If NOT member: keep the current rejection error\n\nThe blocker item must be resolved from the OTHER project's JSONL or store. This requires:\n- Determining the blocker's campfire ID from the cross-campfire ref\n- Opening the store for that campfire\n- Resolving the item\n\nSimpler approach: when both items are in the same CF_HOME's membership list, the user can cd to each project dir. Instead of cross-campfire refs, allow rd dep add to accept items from different project dirs by resolving against ALL known campfire stores. \n\nSIMPLEST approach: detect when the blocker_id matches an item in the CURRENT project (not cross-campfire), or when it's a raw item ID that exists in another project the user has joined. Use the store to search across all campfire memberships.\n\nActually, looking at the code: depAddCmd resolves both items via byIDFromJSONLOrStore(s, arg). The store s is opened from the current CF_HOME. If the user is a member of both campfires, both campfires' messages are in the same store. The resolution should already work IF we remove the IsCrossCampfireRef rejection.\n\nBUT the issue is the item ID format: 'frontend-abc' looks like a regular item ID (prefix-hex), not a cross-campfire ref. Cross-campfire refs have dots: 'acme.frontend.frontend-abc'. Plain item IDs like 'backend-xyz' won't trigger IsCrossCampfireRef.\n\nSo the actual fix is simpler: when both items exist in the same store (same CF_HOME), rd dep add already works IF the items can be resolved. The problem is that byIDFromJSONLOrStore only searches the CURRENT project's JSONL, not all campfires in the store.\n\nReal fix:\n1. Try to resolve both items from current project's JSONL first (existing behavior)\n2. If blocker is not found locally, search across all campfire memberships in the store\n3. If found in another campfire: post the work:block to the CURRENT project's campfire with the blocker's msg_id from the other campfire\n4. For the dep to unblock, rd must check the blocker's status across campfires during state derivation\n\n### Part B: Cross-campfire resolution in state derivation\nFile: pkg/crossdep/resolve.go\n\nCurrently cross-campfire deps produce CrossCampfireWarning (non-blocking). Change: when the user is a member of the blocker's campfire (checkable via store membership), resolve the blocker's current status. If status != done/cancelled, the dep is BLOCKING.\n\nThis requires the state derivation in pkg/resolve/ to call into crossdep with a store that can read across campfires.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do NOT change the campfire protocol — cross-campfire deps are implemented via local resolution\n- Do NOT require items to use dotted cross-campfire ref syntax — plain item IDs should work when resolvable across campfires in the same store\n- Do NOT break existing within-project deps\n- Cross-campfire deps should be displayed with a visual indicator (e.g. [cross] prefix in dep tree output)\n\n## Test\ntest-depth: feature\n1. Create two projects (frontend, backend) under same identity\n2. Create item-A in frontend, item-B in backend\n3. rd dep add item-A item-B (from frontend dir) — should succeed\n4. rd ready (frontend) — item-A should NOT appear (blocked)\n5. rd done item-B (backend) — close the blocker\n6. rd ready (frontend) — item-A should appear (unblocked)\n\n## Agent type\nagent-type: implementer\nartifact-type: code\nmodel: opus","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-cc0","parent_id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p1","title":"Same-owner cross-project deps: allow blocking across campfires you own","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"bfc8aa7f-0b1b-4832-8ca8-f1885f6e93fd","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682649762186627,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"## Outcome\nAll 10 demo scripts (test/demo/01-10) use the new ergonomics. All pass clean. site/index.html updated with fresh transcript examples.\n\n## Design reference\nP8 from conversation context. Continuation of the demo work that produced the current 01-10 scripts.\n\n## Changes per demo\n- ALL: Remove --confirm from rd init calls (P3 makes it unnecessary for local filesystem)\n- ALL multi-identity: Remove rd sync pull after rd join (P2 makes it automatic)\n- 02-team, 04-org-observer, 05-agent-workflow, 06-gate-escalation: Replace pubkey extraction + rd admit with rd invite + rd join \u003ctoken\u003e (P1)\n- 07-hosted-multi-machine: Replace hosted admit ceremony with rd invite token flow (P1). Keep security intruder section.\n- 08-org-naming: Replace admit ceremony with invite token (P1)\n- 09-cattle-workstation: Replace ALL three admit ceremonies (owner rebuild, worker) with invite tokens. This is the biggest cleanup — current script does pubkey extraction 3 times.\n- ALL with rd create in scripts: Replace rd create --json | python3 extraction with direct pipe capture: ITEM=$(rd create 'title' --priority p1 --type task) (P4)\n- 03-multiproject: Add real cross-project dep wiring (P7) — replace the placeholder pattern\n- ALL: Verify no convention server warnings in non-owner output (P5)\n\n## Process\n1. Build rd from current main (with all P1-P7 fixes): go build -o /tmp/rd-demo ./cmd/rd/\n2. Update each demo script with the new patterns\n3. Run each demo, capture transcript to test/demo/output/\n4. Verify all assertions pass\n5. Extract key examples from transcripts, update site/index.html\n6. Run existing unit/e2e tests to verify nothing is broken\n\n## Constraints\n- Do NOT change the demo coverage — all scenarios must still be demonstrated\n- Do NOT remove the security section from demo 07 — intruder rejection is important\n- Do NOT change the output directory structure (test/demo/output/*.txt)\n- Keep the tee_section/run helper pattern — it produces clean transcripts\n\n## Dependencies\nDepends on ALL of: ready-5cd (P2 auto-sync), ready-3ce (P5 suppress warning), ready-b56 (P3 quiet durability), ready-e09 (P4 pipe-friendly), ready-c31 (P1 invite), ready-cc0 (P7 cross-project deps)\n\n## Test\ntest-depth: feature\nAll 10 demos pass clean. No python3 parsing in any script. No --confirm on local init. No rd sync pull after rd join. No pubkey extraction in multi-identity demos. site/index.html reflects new output.\n\n## Agent type\nagent-type: implementer\nartifact-type: code\nmodel: sonnet","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-ce6","parent_id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p1","title":"Rebuild all demos with ergonomic sugar and refresh website","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"e7615dd8-fe00-4bfb-b596-350c7d11527c","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682660703369900,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"## Outcome\nSecurity audit of the rd invite / rd join token flow confirms no auth bypass, key leakage, or TOCTOU vulnerabilities.\n\n## Scope\nReview ready-c31 (rd invite implementation). The invite token embeds a pre-provisioned ed25519 private key + campfire ID. Security surfaces to audit:\n\n1. **Token contents**: Private key in a portable string. Can it be intercepted? Replay? Used after revocation?\n2. **TOCTOU**: Between rd invite (admit pubkey) and rd join (use privkey), can the admitted slot be hijacked?\n3. **Key lifecycle**: Is the pre-provisioned key properly scoped to one campfire? Can it be reused for other campfires?\n4. **Expiry enforcement**: Does TTL actually prevent join after expiry? What clock skew is tolerable?\n5. **Revocation**: If token leaks, can the identity be revoked (rd revoke)? Does revocation propagate?\n6. **Identity collision**: Can two invite tokens create conflicting identities?\n7. **Audit trail**: Does the invite leave a traceable audit trail (who invited, when, which key)?\n\n## Agent type\nagent-type: sweeper-security\nartifact-type: code\nmodel: opus","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-f27","parent_id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p0","title":"Security review: invite token flow (P1)","type":"review"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"a0136778-d253-42a0-9ee3-f638f8112344","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775682670398099900,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"Sweep all P1-P7 changes for security vulnerabilities. Focus on invite token, cross-project dep resolution, and any new auth surfaces. agent-type: sweeper-security. model: sonnet.","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-eec","parent_id":"ready-3d6","priority":"p2","title":"Security sweep: all ergonomic changes","type":"review"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
