{"msg_id":"46ba8383-6e77-4ff5-ae19-7e16f10dbf04","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775695307870391650,"operation":"work:update","payload":{"priority":"p0","target":"9569228c-afb1-4ead-b428-56354b20d9cc","title":"Walk-up config in demos: zero-ceremony agent identity — cd into project, rd just works"},"tags":["work:update"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"7b92e7c4-f8bd-48b5-948e-1d32ee0e5d7b","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775695371801521090,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"New demo (11 or replace 03) showing the walk-up config system as the agent isolation primitive. Scenarios: (1) Owner inits project, identity resolves from .cf/config.toml in project dir — no CF_HOME needed. (2) Two agents in sibling worktrees of the same repo — each gets its own .cf/config.toml with a different identity, both inherit the project campfire from the parent. (3) Agent spawned in a subdirectory — config walks up, finds project root, resolves identity. No env vars in any command. The demo should make the point explicit: the filesystem hierarchy IS the coordination primitive. Parent dirs set context, child dirs inherit it, sibling dirs isolate from each other. This is how you run 5 agents on one repo without them stepping on each other's identity.","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-9df","priority":"p0","title":"Demo: filesystem hierarchy isolation and coordination — walk-up config for agents","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
{"msg_id":"174d0e21-5ffb-4433-baf2-e6c8a5c94b73","campfire_id":"670f815159f88220981e79b7cbbc5e98432d73771c215b7d2082ec818b74329a","timestamp":1775695556754906044,"operation":"work:create","payload":{"context":"Currently rd's CFHome() only checks: --cf-home flag, CF_HOME env, ~/.cf, ~/.campfire. It does NOT walk up the directory tree. But projectRoot() DOES walk up (.campfire/root). This mismatch means agents still need CF_HOME= env vars for identity isolation.\n\nThe cf 0.16 config cascade spec says: compiled defaults → ~/.cf/config.toml → ancestor .cf/config.toml → project .cf/config.toml → CF_HOME env → CLI flags. The protocol library (protocol.Init) may already support walk-up — rd just doesn't use it.\n\nFix: In cmd/rd/root.go CFHome(), add directory walk-up BEFORE falling back to ~/.cf. Walk up from cwd looking for .cf/ directories. If found, use that as CF_HOME. This means:\n\n  /project/\n    .campfire/root        (project campfire — already walks up)\n    worktree-a/.cf/       (agent-1 identity — NEW: walks up stops here)\n    worktree-b/.cf/       (agent-2 identity — NEW: walks up stops here)\n\nAgent in worktree-a/ gets: identity from worktree-a/.cf/, campfire from project/.campfire/root. Zero env vars.\n\nResolution order after fix: --cf-home flag → CF_HOME env → walk-up .cf/ from cwd → ~/.cf → ~/.campfire → ~/.cf default.\n\nTest: create two sibling dirs each with .cf/identity.json, run rd from each, verify different identities resolve while same project campfire is found.","for":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd","id":"ready-c4b","priority":"p0","title":"Walk-up identity resolution: make rd CFHome() walk up .cf/ directories (match cf 0.16 config cascade)","type":"task"},"tags":["work:create"],"sender":"1e224c14bc7959bf6bec7d4e563389b6c3d3e9255ad206df1ba60cdc52197ffd"}
